<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Do</strong>&nbsp;</h4>



<ol>
<li>Obtain a flat bench and a dumbbell with an appropriate weight for your fitness level.</li>



<li>Place your right hand and knee on the bench. Your left foot should be flat on the ground. Hinge forward at the hips with a flat back and extend your left arm to grab the dumbbell. This is your starting position.</li>



<li>Begin to lift your elbow up and back until it reaches hip height. Pause briefly at the top of the movement.</li>



<li>Slowly descend and straighten your arm back down to the starting position.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Repeat on this side until you’ve completed the appropriate amount of repetitions.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Switch to the opposite side.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul>
<li>Quality over quantity! Lifting too heavy may cause you to rely on momentum, reducing muscle activation.</li>



<li>Keep your back flat and your head aligned with your spine to avoid strain.</li>



<li>Pause and squeeze at the top of the movement to engage your muscles fully.</li>
</ul>



